---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config.ts';
---

<Base title={SITE.title} description={SITE.description}>
  <Nav />
  <main id="main">
    <Hero />

    <Section id="problem" heading="The problem">
      <p>
        Humanoids, cobots, and autonomous systems increasingly use AI to
        operate outside industrial robot cages and controlled factory
        environments. These robots are increasingly driven by AI rather than
        hand-coded logic.
      </p>
      <p>
        As these robots take on continuously improving artificial brains, they
        become more capable but less predictable in what they will do. Without
        dependable ways to constrain what robots can do, risk is hard to
        bound, deployment near people slows, and accountability is difficult
        to establish. Addressing these problems requires a layer between the
        AI's decisions and the robot's motion that measures, records, and
        bounds what the robot does.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section id="what-we-do" heading="What we do" variant="tinted">
      <p>
        MindMotion is building runtime software for AI-driven robotics. Our
        work draws on more than fifteen years of research and engineering in
        robot control and a peer-reviewed methodological foundation in the
        field.
      </p>
      <p>
        MindMotion software operates at the interface between the brain and
        the body, where decisions become motion. At that interface, the
        software measures, records, and bounds what the robot does, regardless
        of what the AI decides or how it evolves.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section id="why-now" heading="Why now">
      <p>
        Robots are entering human environments faster than the methods to
        govern them are maturing. The brains controlling those robots are
        changing more frequently than the processes used to evaluate them.
        New questions are emerging about how robot behavior should be governed
        and who is accountable when something goes wrong.
      </p>
      <p>
        Aviation, automotive, and computing each reached a moment when
        execution had to be separated from decision-making. Robotics is at the
        same moment.
      </p>
    </Section>

    {/* Insights preview section wired in Step 4 once content collection exists. */}
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>
